@node introduction "Dizzy? What's that then?"
@prev main
@next features
@toc  main

                           @{b}@{u}Introduction to Dizzy@{uu}@{ub}


Dizzy was written to make life a bit easier for Fidonet BBS sysops (and
users!) with Internet access who regularly upload files from Aminet to
a Fidonet BBS.

All good BBS software packages will check uploaded files for a FILE_ID.DIZ
to use as the files description. Dizzy's main function is to convert the
Aminet .README file to a FILE_ID.DIZ  for easy upload to a BBS. 

Dizzy will also convert the downloaded files/archives using you're
@{" PREFERREDPACKER " link preferredpacker}, and, if you want, delete the old archives and readmes.


@endnode

@node features
@prev introduction
@next install
@toc  main

                                 @{b}@{u}Features@{uu}@{ub}


Will accept an alternative @{" CONFIG " link config} file as program argument, so you can set
up various configs for different situations.

No need for user interaction once config has been set, so can be run from a
cron script.

Switch on or off the @{" INFO " link info} , @{" DELETEREADME " link deletereadme} , @{" DELETEOLDARC " link deleteoldarc} and @{" REPLACEDIZ " link replacediz}
functions.

User can set up additional @{" ARC " link arc} types

Converts LHA files to LZX, or vice versa, using @{" PREFERREDPACKER " link preferredpacker}

Adds you're own @{" BBSAD " link bbsad} to the archive.

User configurable @{" SOURCEDIR " link sourcedir} and @{" DESTDIR " link destdir}

User configurable search @{" PATTERN " link pattern} and @{" DIZNAME " link dizname}

User can choose which @{" TYPE " link type} of description lines go into the File_ID.DIZ

User configurable @{" DEFAULTDESC " link defaultdesc} if you're description @{" TYPE " link type} isn't found in
the readme

@{" TEMPDISK " link tempdisk} can be in RAM: to speed things up if you've got enough memory



@endnode


@node install
@prev features
@next requires
@toc  main
                             @{b}@{u}Installing Dizzy@{uu}@{ub}

All the required files will unpack to a drawer called DIZZY

If you want to use the default settings, set up an assign to DIZZY: with
the path of this drawer.

That's it :)


@endnode


@node requires
@prev install
@next usage
@toc  main
                           @{b}@{u}Dizzy's Requirements@{uu}@{ub}

An Amiga, probably A1200 or above.

Around 150k of free memory to run, more if you want to speed things up by 
working in ram - see @{" TEMPDISK " link tempdisk}

Some Aminet files to process.

I suppose it probably needs a Hard Drive, there's no reason it shouldn't
work on floppies, but it would be virtually unusable! As Dizzy is designed
mainly for sysops with Internet access, I can't see this being a problem :)


@endnode


@node usage
@prev requires
@next author
@toc  main
                                @{b}@{u}Using Dizzy@{uu}@{ub}

Edit you're @{" CONFIG " link config}.

Run it from the CLI by typing 'Dizzy' (assuming you've set up a path to it
or its in the Current Directory!)

To use an alternative CONFIG , type 'Dizzy yourconfignameandpath'




@endnode

