@node config
@prev disclaimer
@next command
@toc  main


                             @{b}@{u}Dizzy Config File@{uu}@{ub}


Dizzy will accept one argument when called, the name of a config file to
use. e.g. 'Dizzy DH0:Temp/Dizzy.config'

If you call Dizzy without any arguments, it will first of all look for a
file called 'Dizzy.config' in the same directory as itself, and if it fails
to find this file, it will look for 'S:Dizzy.config' If none of these files
exist, Dizzy will not run.


Each line in the config file should consist of a @{" COMMAND " link command} followed by its
arguments. Dizzy will ignore blank lines and lines beginning with a
semi-colon ( ; )

If any of the commands are not present in the config file, Dizzy will use
its internal default setting.

Any unrecognised commands or invalid arguments will stop Dizzy running.

@endnode

@node command
@prev config
@next info
@toc  config
                                 @{b}@{u}Commands:@{uu}@{ub}

                    @{" INFO " link info}                     @{" SOURCEDIR " link sourcedir}
                    @{" DELETEREADME " link deletereadme}             @{" DESTDIR " link destdir}
                    @{" DELETEOLDARC " link deleteoldarc}             @{" BBSAD " link bbsad}
                    @{" REPLACEDIZ " link replacediz}               @{" TEMPDISK " link tempdisk}
                    
                    @{" PREFERREDPACKER " link preferredpacker}          @{" PATTERN " link pattern}
                    @{" ARC " link arc}                      @{" DIZNAME " link dizname}
                    @{" DEFAULTDESC " link defaultdesc}              @{" TYPE " link type}

@endnode


@node info
@prev command
@next deletereadme
@toc  config
                                   @{b}@{u}INFO@{uu}@{ub}


INFO is a simple switch command, it can be either ON of OFF

INFO ON   -  Dizzy will print progress messages while running.

INFO OFF  -  Dizzy will only print a message if a serious error occurs.


Default is ON

@endnode

@node deletereadme
@prev info
@next deleteoldarc
@toc  config
                               @{b}@{u}DELETEREADME@{uu}@{ub}


DELETEREADME is a simple switch command, it can be either ON of OFF

DELETEREADME ON   -  Dizzy will delete any processed .readme files.

DELETEREADME OFF  -  Dizzy will leave the .readmes.


Default is OFF

@endnode

@node deleteoldarc
@prev deletereadme
@next replacediz
@toc  config
                               @{b}@{u}DELETEOLDARC@{uu}@{ub}


DELETEOLDARC is a simple switch command, it can be either ON of OFF

DELETEOLDARC ON   -  Dizzy will delete the old archive/file

DELETEOLDARC OFF  -  Dizzy will leave the old archive/file.


Default is OFF


Note: 

If Dizzy is only adding a File_ID.DIZ and or @{" BBSAD " link bbsad} to an existing
archive without converting to a different packer type, then it knows not to
delete the old archive :)

@endnode


@node replacediz
@prev deleteoldarc
@next sourcedir
@toc  config
                                @{b}@{u}REPLACEDIZ@{uu}@{ub}


REPLACEDIZ is a simple switch command, it can be either ON of OFF

REPLACEDIZ ON   -  If there is already a File_ID.DIZ within the archive,
                   Dizzy will overwrite it with you're new one.

REPLACEDIZ OFF  -  Dizzy won't overwrite an existing File_ID.DIZ


Default is OFF

@endnode


@node sourcedir
@prev replacediz
@next destdir
@toc  config
                                 @{b}@{u}SOURCEDIR@{uu}@{ub}

SOURCEDIR sets the directory where Dizzy looks for the files to convert.


Default:  DIZZY:Downloads

Example:  SOURCEDIR DH0:Internet/Downloads

Note:
      If you use the default setting, you will need to have DIZZY: assigned.

      DO NOT surround the filename with quotes.


@endnode

@node destdir
@prev sourcedir
@next bbsad
@toc  config
                                  @{b}@{u}DESTDIR@{uu}@{ub}

DESTDIR sets the directory where Dizzy puts the converted archives.


Default:  DIZZY:Procesed

Example:  DESTDIR DH0:BBS/Uploads

Note:
      DESTDIR can be the same as SOURCEDIR if required.

      DESTDIR cannot be a read-only device, e.g. a CDROM - Obviously!

      If you use the default setting, you will need to have DIZZY: assigned.

      DO NOT surround the filename with quotes.

@endnode

@node bbsad
@prev destdir
@next tempdisk
@toc  config
                                   @{b}@{u}BBSAD@{uu}@{ub}

BBSAD is the full path and name of you're BBS Advert.

If you don't want to add an advert, omit this command from the config.

Default:  none

Example:  BBSAD Dizzy:Dreamtime.AD3

Note:
     DO NOT enclose the name in quotes.

     If the file doesn't exist, Dizzy will carry on anyway.

@endnode

@node tempdisk
@prev bbsad
@next pattern
@toc  config
                                 @{b}@{u}TEMPDISK@{uu}@{ub}

TEMPDISK is the path and name of the temporary drawer required by Dizzy to
unpack the archives for conversion. If you have enough free memory (at
least as much as the unpacked file size of the largest archive you'll ever
come across!), this can be in RAM: for extra speed.

IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT, IF THERE IS NOT ENOUGH ROOM ON THE TEMPDISK TO
FULLY UNPACK THE ARCHIVE, DIZZY WILL NOT STOP. IT WILL PACK UP THE
PARTIAL ARCHIVE AND CARRY ON AS IF NOTHING HAS GONE WRONG! IF YOU USE RAM: 
MAKE SURE YOU HAVE PLENTY SPARE!


Default:  DIZZY:DizzyTemp

Example:  TEMPDISK RAM:DizzyTemp


Note:
     The actual name of the drawer doesn't make much difference, but Dizzy
     will NOT run if you specify an existing drawer - this is beacause
     Dizzy deletes the temporary drawer and all its contents when finished.

     If Dizzy should fail for any reason, it may not delete the temporary
     drawer. This will stop Dizzy from running until the temporary drawer
     has been deleted.


@endnode

@node pattern
@prev tempdisk
@next dizname
@toc  config
                                  @{b}@{u}PATTERN@{uu}@{ub}

PATTERN - Is the Amigados filepattern you want to search for. Most of the
time you will use #?.readme , but this could be used to limit Dizzy to
certain files.

Default:  #?.readme

Examples: PATTERN a#?.readme , PATTERN a|b#?.readme


@endnode

@node dizname
@prev pattern
@next defaultdesc
@toc  config
                                  @{b}@{u}DIZNAME@{uu}@{ub}

DIZNAME allows you to change the name of the File_ID.Diz to something else.
Why? Someone, somewhere will want to do it ;)

Default:  FILE_ID.DIZ

Example:  DIZNAME Shortreadme


@endnode

@node defaultdesc
@prev dizname
@next preferredpacker
@toc  config
                                @{b}@{u}DEFAULTDESC@{uu}@{ub}

DEFAULTDESC is only used if Dizzy can't find any lines matching any of your
description @{" TYPES " link type} 

Default:  "Recent Aminet Download"

Example:   DEFAULTDESC "Latest files, straight from the Internet"

Note:
     String MUST be enclosed in quotes.


@endnode

@node preferredpacker
@prev defaultdesc
@next type
@toc  config
                              @{b}@{u}PREFERREDPACKER@{uu}@{ub}

PREFERREDPACKER lets you choose which packer you want to use to pack the
new archive. 

Default:  LZX

Example:  LHA


Note:
     This MUST match one of you're @{" ARC " link arc} entries, with a
     valid pack command - You can't pack them up using TXT :)


@endnode

@node type
@prev preferredpacker
@next arc
@toc  config
                                   @{b}@{u}TYPE@{uu}@{ub}

TYPE lets you decide which type of description lines you want to put into
the FILE_ID.DIZ. It takes three argument:

A string - e.g. SHORT:
A switch - ON or OFF, tells Dizzy whether you want to skip past the first
           word in the description line. 
A number - The maximum number of characters youu want in this line (0 for
           the full line regardless of length)


Two TYPEs are defined by default. If Dizzy finds a TYPE command in the
config, both the default TYPEs are cleared and will have to be entered in
the config if you still require them.


Default:  SHORT: ON 80
          TYPE:  OFF 0

Example:  SHORT: ON   0
          AUTHOR: OFF 0
          TYPE:   OFF 0

Note:
     If Dizzy fails to find any TYPE, it carries on and looks for the
     others. If it can't find ANY of you're TYPEs, it will use you're
     @{" DEFAULTDESC " link defaultdesc}


@endnode


@node arc
@prev type
@next arc
@toc  config
                                    @{b}@{u}ARC@{uu}@{ub}

ARC lets you set up new archivers/filetypes for use by Dizzy. 
This is a powerful command and can probably be used to provide some very
spectacular crashes ;)

Each ARC command requires 4 arguments:

File Extension
Unpack Command
Add To Archive Command
Replace Command

Dizzy uses the first argument, the file extension, to recognise each
different filetype. The other arguments should be reasonably apparent, and
the default settings should be fine for most people. You may want to remove
the -q (quiet) switches to watch LHA, LZH or LZX unpacking/packing if you
think something's not doing what it should.

For filetypes such as TXT or JPG, use "NONE" for the unpack, addpack and
replace arguments.


Default:  ARC "LHA"  "LHA -q x"  "LHA -q -r a"     "LHA -q r"
          ARC "LZH"  "LHA -q x"  "LHA -q -r -0 a"  "LHA -q r"
          ARC "LZX"  "LZX -q x"  "LZX -q -r a"     "LZX -q -r u"
          ARC "TXT"  "NONE"      "NONE"            "NONE"
          ARC "JPG"  "NONE"      "NONE"            "NONE"
          ARC "GIF"  "NONE"      "NONE"            "NONE"

Example:  ARC  "FAQ"  "NONE"  "NONE"  "NONE" 


Note:
     If Dizzy finds an ARC command in the config, it deletes ALL the
     default ARCs. If you add a new ARC type, you must include ARC
     statements for all the default archivers. All the default ARC commands
     are included in the example config for this purpose.

     @{" PREFERREDPACKER " link preferredpacker} checks through the ARC list for a matching File
     Extension with valid unpack/pack commands.



@endnode


